Certainly, here are two examples of monads in JavaScript and C#:

JavaScript:

```javascript
class Maybe {
  constructor(value) {
    this.value = value;
  }

  static of(value) {
    return new Maybe(value);
  }

  map(fn) {
    return this.value ? Maybe.of(fn(this.value)) : Maybe.of(null);
  }

  chain(fn) {
    return this.value ? fn(this.value) : Maybe.of(null);
  }
}
```

C#:
```csharp
public class Maybe<T>
{
    public T Value { get; }
    public bool HasValue { get; }

    public Maybe(T value)
    {
        Value = value;
        HasValue = value != null;
    }

    public Maybe<U> Select<U>(Func<T, U> selector)
    {
        return HasValue ? new Maybe<U>(selector(Value)) : new Maybe<U>(default(U));
    }

    public Maybe<U> SelectMany<U>(Func<T, Maybe<U>> selector)
    {
        return HasValue ? selector(Value) : new Maybe<U>(default(U));
    }
}
```

Sure! Here are examples of the Maybe monad in JavaScript and C#:

JavaScript:

class Maybe {
  constructor(value) {
    this.value = value;
  }

  static of(value) {
    return new Maybe(value);
  }

  map(fn) {
    return this.value === null || this.value === undefined
      ? Maybe.of(null)
      : Maybe.of(fn(this.value));
  }

  join() {
    return this.value === null || this.value === undefined
      ? Maybe.of(null)
      : this.value;
  }

  chain(fn) {
    return this.map(fn).join();
  }
}


C#:

public class Maybe<T>
{
    public T Value { get; }

    private Maybe(T value)
    {
        Value = value;
    }

    public static Maybe<T> Of(T value)
    {
        return value == null ? new Maybe<T>(value) : None;
    }

    public static readonly Maybe<T> None = new Maybe<T>(default(T));

    public Maybe<U> Map<U>(Func<T, U> map)
    {
        return this == None ? None : Of(map(Value));
    }

    public Maybe<U> Bind<U>(Func<T, Maybe<U>> bind)
    {
        return this == None ? None : bind(Value);
    }
}

Note that in both examples, the Maybe monad is implemented as a wrapper type around an optional value. The map and chain methods provide a way to transform the value and sequence operations, respectively, while abstracting away the details of handling missing values.

Sure, here's an example of a basic first loop setter in JavaScript that calculates the tempo based on the time between a start and end point:

```javascript
// Get the start and end time in milliseconds
const startTime = Date.now();
// Wait for the user to indicate the end of the loop, for example by clicking a button
// or pressing a key
// Then get the end time in milliseconds
const endTime = Date.now();

// Calculate the time difference in seconds
const timeDiffInSeconds = (endTime - startTime) / 1000;

// Calculate the tempo based on the time difference
// For example, assuming a 4/4 time signature, we could set the tempo to the number of
// beats per minute based on the number of bars (or measures) in the loop
const numberOfBars = 4; // For example, assume a loop of 4 bars
const beatsPerBar = 4; // Assume a 4/4 time signature
const tempo = Math.round(numberOfBars / timeDiffInSeconds * beatsPerBar * 60);

// Display the calculated tempo
console.log(`The tempo is ${tempo} BPM`);
```

Note that this is just an example and you may need to adapt it to fit your specific use case, such as adjusting the time signature, number of bars, or tempo calculation formula. Additionally, you may need to implement additional functionality to handle user input for starting and stopping the loop, or to set the tempo in your looping software.

Gladly! Here's a basic implementation of a first loop setter in JavaScript. This code snippet uses the Web Audio API, which is supported in modern browsers.

    // Create audio context
    const audioContext = new AudioContext();

    // Variables to store loop start and end times
    let loopStart = null;
    let loopEnd = null;

    // Function to start the loop
    function startLoop() {
      // Record the current audio context time as the loop start time
      loopStart = audioContext.currentTime;
      console.log('Loop started at', loopStart);
    }

    // Function to end the loop and calculate the tempo (BPM)
    function endLoop() {
      // Check if the loop has started
      if (loopStart === null) {
        console.log('Loop not started');
        return;
      }

      // Record the current audio context time as the loop end time
      loopEnd = audioContext.currentTime;
      console.log('Loop ended at', loopEnd);

      // Calculate the loop duration and tempo (BPM)
      const loopDuration = loopEnd - loopStart;
      const tempo = 60 / loopDuration;
      console.log('Loop duration:', loopDuration, 'seconds');
      console.log('Tempo:', tempo, 'BPM');

      // Reset the loop start time for the next loop
      loopStart = null;
    }

    // Example usage
    startLoop();
    setTimeout(endLoop, 2000); // End the loop after 2 seconds

This code creates an audio context to work with the Web Audio API and defines two functions, startLoop() and endLoop(). The startLoop() function sets the loop start time based on the current audio context time. The endLoop() function sets the loop end time, calculates the loop duration and the tempo (in BPM) based on the loop duration, and then resets the loop start time.

You can use the startLoop() and endLoop() functions in your application to set the first loop and determine the tempo. In the example usage, the loop is ended after 2 seconds using setTimeout().

